A nozzle understood to be N11 displayed discoloration suggestive of carbon contamination and requires pickling / passivation. The nozzle was observed to be apparently incorrectly labelled with marker pen as N6 and N1.
Recommended action but no details added to report. To be reviewed on site.

The repair nameplate has not been stamped with the past two repair dates.
Wrong Revision OF DRAWING NOT RESOLVED
Drawings referenced in ITP were K-36090 Rev C & K-36091 Rev D with the later also included in NDT reports. SOW A1 503 Rev 3 states the design drawing as being K-36091 Rev 1
Job number not on bundle or bonnet, however equipment hard stamped.
John M Carlisle, International Welding Specialist and AS 1796 Welding Supervisor was used on the repair outage
The ITP was not signed for this inspection until further clarifications were made prereporting.

Several Tubes were pulled, due to being externally corroded. Refer to figure 8 for Tasocs Tube map.
Four distorted tubes were highlighted on the 20/01/2014.
The distortion was located approximately 300-500 away from the nickel tube sheet. Refer to photographs 3 to 6 above.
The Nickel Tube sheet was measured at 28, as specified on drawing K-36091 Rev E.
Tube sheet thickness to be clarified
Tube sheet thickness to be clarified

Externally there is minor indentations noted around the majority of bolt holes, and light mechanical damage
noted elsewhere, otherwise appeared to be in satisfactory condition.

Shell Hydro completed
22/01/2014. Tube Hydro completed
23/01/2014
Repack pipe support on condensate line 50-SC-3C008-C1A-ih

Main girth flange gramophone finish has some isolated areas if pinhole like pitting, recommended reinstating
finish to 3.2-6.4m (Note 9 drawing K-36091) ensuring minimum step height of 2.0mm is maintained as per
drawing K-36091

Tube bores where tubes have been removed were not seen as the stubs remain in the tube bores. These need
to be reviewed for suitability of re-tubing after tube stubs have been removed.
Gramophone finish appears to have some light corrosion grooves in the sealing area, recommended
reinstating finish to 1.6m as per drawing K-36091.
Rear of tube sheet has corrosion scale which is flaking off in large segments, recommend removing scale prior
to installing new tubes (and possibly coating prior to re-tube).

There is corrosion wastage up to 4.6mm on the gramophone finish, wastage extends up to 20mm into the
gramophone finish and covers approx. half of the circumference (combined). Extensive weld repair and remachining will be required to reinstate this tube sheet.
Preferential grooving noted around some the tube bores estimated to be approx. up to 2mm deep

Remaining tubes appear to be in satisfactory condition however of the 10 remaining U-tubes 6 were found
with isolated pitting up to 0.5mm deep, which will need to be considered for removal  remaining wall
thicknesses may be below 2mm in these areas.
Baffles have varying degrees of wastage, with preferential pitting around tube bores, I have marked up the
more significant of these areas i.e. .2mm wastage, however only the ones with full wall wastage on the outer
radius should be re-welded as a minimum to reinstate the web.
Some tie rods have been removed. Remaining rods are in varying stages of wastage, with some deformed.
The welds long and circ were prominent, there were no visual welding defects evident.

Multiple linear indications and pinholes noted on Metlabs MT report 17TAS035-01, recommend repair by
removing indication(s) with die-grinder, weld repair and reinstate to nominal surface/ weld profile as per
drawing K-36091.

Internally surfaces generally appeared in satisfactory condition overall. There is isolated areas of localised
grouped pitting of approx. 0.5 to 1.0mm deep which is primarily noted around welds. It is recommended to
blend out the pitting, where the pitting is associated with welds - pitting is to be removed, however where
excessive dressing has occurred, weld repair shall be carried out to reinstate the weld profile as designated on
drawing K-36091.
The coating was in a satisfactory condition with only one isolated spot of chipped coating on the west side

INSPECTION_COMMENTS:
Both data plates attached to vessel were found secure with all information clear and legible; one data plate attached
to shell with other one attached to top dome.
Design registration number has not been stamped onto either plate; recommend that design and plant registration
numbers once registered are stamped accordingly

The vessel is identified by the equipment number stencilled on the can section top and is stamped on the data plate.
The data plate is clear and legible but does not contain either a design or plant registration number. There is no
evidence in the plant equipment file that the design and plant are registered. At the last inspection of this vessel it
was requested that the design and vessel should be registered with WorkSafe WA

The vessel was identified by data plates attached to shell and top dome, stencilled number on shell is becoming
illegible (Fig 6). The data plates were legible stamped with both the plant and design registration number. No hazardous chemical label was found at the time (the only one labelled in vicinity is at S321 E location )
The vessel was found free of damage or deformation, the external paint coating has some minor breakdown but is in generally in fair condition.

INSPECTION_COMMENTS: The shell appears to be straight with no evidence of distortion noted. No corrosion.

The vessels external painting was found generally in an acceptable condition. Small areas of paint loss with
associated minor surface corrosion were noted on the shell and both domes, its recommended to spot paint affected areas. It was noted coating was not applied on repaired nozzle N6 and associated shell border.

Nozzle N5 flange face was re-machined. The machined flange face was inspected and found visually
acceptable. MPI was not sighted at the time of inspection.

As with other vessel installation inspections completed recently, short bolting was evident.
Top dome to shell and Nozzle N1 exhibits this problem, at least two threads should protrude through nut for full
strength of nut to be realised.
Vessel supports were visually inspected and found to be in good condition with no distortion or cracking noted.

No hold down bolts were in place or secured, one bolt was partially installed on an angle with remaining three bolts
not installed; this was reported to area supervisor who was aware of problem due to misalignment with supports.
Review of hold down bolts conducted on July 4th by R. Byrne noted all four bolts as installed and secure.
INTERNAL INSPECTION SUMMARY
The vessel was found to be securely bolted to the supporting structure.

The support to shell attachment welds appeared to be in satisfactory condition and the vessel was found securely
bolted to its supporting structure.
Earth strap connected to north support leg

INSPECTION_COMMENTS:
All assessable areas on nozzles, internal shell and dome surface areas were visually inspected with internal condition
noted in as new condition.

At the initial inspection areas of the shell above the tube sheet were found with remnants of the paint coating still
adhering. Similarly the internal surface of the top dome was largely stripped of its paint coating. There was a large
clump of paint fragments in the bottom dome.
An inspection of the repaired paint coating showed that:
The paint had been over applied and was thick and had run in many places and not in accordance with the paint
manufacturers specifications.
